  "prompt": "Why does WiFi turn on in airplane mode?",
  "response": "When you enable **Airplane Mode** on your smartphone or device, it typically disables all wireless communication features, including cellular, Bluetooth, and Wi-Fi. However, some devices allow you to **manually re-enable Wi-Fi** while still keeping Airplane Mode active. Here\u2019s why this happens and why it\u2019s designed this way:\n\n### 1. **Airplane Mode vs. Wi-Fi Use in Flights**\n   - Originally, Airplane Mode was designed to disable all wireless signals to comply with aviation regulations, as radio transmissions could potentially interfere with aircraft systems.\n   - However, many airlines now offer **in-flight Wi-Fi**, which operates on frequencies that are safe for use during flight. To use this service, passengers can turn Wi-Fi back on while still keeping Airplane Mode enabled.\n\n### 2. **Device Flexibility**\n   - Allowing Wi-Fi to be turned on in Airplane Mode gives users the flexibility to use Wi-Fi for internet access or other purposes (e.g., streaming, messaging apps) without enabling cellular connectivity, which is often restricted during flights.\n\n### 3. **Regulatory Compliance**\n   - Airlines and regulators have approved certain Wi-Fi systems for in-flight use. By keeping Airplane Mode on but enabling Wi-Fi, users can comply with safety regulations while still accessing approved services.\n\n### 4. **Energy Saving**\n   - Airplane Mode reduces battery consumption by disabling power-hungry features like cellular radios. Re-enabling Wi-Fi allows for internet access without significantly impacting battery life.\n\n### Summary:\nWiFi can be turned on in Airplane Mode because it allows users to access in-flight Wi-Fi services or connect to Wi-Fi networks in other situations without enabling cellular radios. This design balances regulatory compliance with user convenience.",
